The black box in your car?
While U.S. road designers struggle to find money to repair a crumbling highway network, many are beginning to see a solution in a small black box that fits easily into your car’s dashboard.
The devices that track every mile a motorist drives and transmit this information to the authorities are at the heart of a controversial effort by Washington and state planning authorities to renovate the outdated system of financing America’s main roads.
The usually drab design of highways at once sparked intense debate and the emergence of various associations.
Libertarians met with groups of environmentalists and lobbied for the government to use these small boxes to record mileage and perhaps where you are going - and then use that information to build a tax bill.
The tea party was horrified.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also deeply concerned and has mentioned a number of privacy issues.
And while Congress cannot agree on whether to proceed, some states are not waiting for anything.
Over the next decade, they discover how they can move to a system where the driver pays per kilometre of the road they’re driving on.
Thousands of motorists have already taken their black boxes, some of which have GPS tracking, for testing.
This is a real necessity for our nation.
“This is not a matter of choosing too much,” said Hasan Ikhrata, executive director of the Southern California Civil Service Association, which plans to start monitoring every California motorist’s mileage for the state in 2025.
This will change the way we pay our taxes.
This technology is used for this.
The incentive is that the Road Trust Fund, funded by taxes that Americans pay at gas stations, is at an all-time low.
Americans aren’t buying as much gasoline as they used to.
Cars travel many more miles per gallon.
The federal tax rate of 18.4 cents per gallon has not increased in the past 20 years.
Due to the current high price of gasoline, politicians are reluctant to raise the tax even by a single cent.
“The gas tax is just not sustainable,” said Lee Munnich, a transport policy expert at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently placed a tracking device in 500 cars to test this system of paying per kilometer traveled.
“In the long run, this seems to be the most logical alternative,” he said.
Experts call it a user fee according to the number of kilometers traveled.
It’s no surprise that urban liberals like the idea, as taxes can be used to change driver behavior patterns, which, for example, can help reduce traffic congestion and greenhouse gas emissions.
Californian designers look to this system to plan strategies to meet the goals set in ambitious global warming laws.
But Republican Bill Shuster (a representative of Pennsylvania), chairman of the Transportation Committee, said he also sees this as the most functional long-term alternative.
The Reason Foundation’s free market leaders are also open to the idea that drivers will pay for mileage.
“It’s not a tax that disappears in a black hole,” said Adrian Moore, senior vice president of strategy at Reason.
People pay directly for what they get.
The initiative is also backed by two former U.S. transportation ministers who urged Congress in 2011 to move toward paying per kilometre.
The U.S. Senate last year approved a $90 million pilot project to include about 10,000 cars.
However, the House of Representatives rejected the proposal and did so because of concerns from rural lawmakers representing sections of the population, whose daily life often means traveling many miles to work outside the city.
However, several states and cities are moving forward on their own.
Oregon is the world’s largest experiment involving 5,000 drivers.
These drivers will soon start paying taxes on mileage, instead of a tax on gasoline.
Nevada has already completed the pilot project.
New York is researching the project.
Illinois is trying to do this to a limited extent on trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes 17 state ministries of transportation, along with coastal states in the east (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia, and Florida) are studying how they can implement this change.
However, this concept is not just for supporters.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer cars were equipped recently, drivers were concerned that the government was able to monitor their every move.
"The concerns about Big Brother-type surveillance and similar issues were a big concern," said Alauddin Khan, who heads strategy and operations management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
It wasn't something that people wanted.
As the trial project progressed, the American Civil Liberties Union in Nevada warned on its website: “It would be very easy to turn these devices into full-fledged surveillance devices.”
There is no need to build a huge cumbersome technological infrastructure, which will inevitably expand to record the daily trips and arrivals of individuals.
Nevada is among the few states trying to find available technology that would allow the state to track how many kilometers the car will run, but not exactly when and where.
If you can do that, Khan said, the public will be calmer.
The hunt for such technology has led some state agencies to a small company in California called True Mileage.
The company was not initially involved in helping the government tax drivers.
She wanted to break into the emerging market for statutory liability insurance, where drivers would pay based on how much they drive.
But this device they’re testing attracts the attention of road network designers because it doesn’t use GPS and only delivers a limited amount of information that is regularly uploaded using a modem.
“People will be more willing to go for it if you don’t track their speed and their location,” says Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage.
There have been a number of major errors in some of these pilot programs.
There are much cheaper and less intrusive ways to do this.
In Oregon, designers experiment with giving drivers a choice.
They can choose devices with or without GPS.
Or they do not have to take any equipment and instead choose to pay a flat fee based on the average mileage of all residents of the state.
In other places, they hope the cautious public will embrace the concept if the device can do more, not less.
In New York City, traffic officials are trying to develop a tax device that would be equipped to pay extra parking hours fees, provide mileage-based insurance, and collect other drivers' speed data so motorists can avoid traffic jams.
“Motorists will be willing to get involved because of the value of the benefits offered to them,” reads the city’s projection document.
However, some transport designers would like to know if all discussions about paying per kilometer are not just a giant proxy problem.
Officials from the San Francisco Bay Area Metropolitan Transportation Committee say Congress could easily solve the problem of the bankrupt Road Trust Fund by raising the gasoline tax.
A one-time or annual tax could be imposed on drivers of hybrid or other cars that do not consume much fuel, so they will pay a fair share.
“There is no need for radical surgery when aspirin is abundantly enough,” said Randy Rentschler, director of the Committee on Legislation and Public Affairs.
