The judge ruled that police officers violated the civil rights of tens of thousands of people when they wrongly targeted blacks and Hispanics as part of their program to stop and search people.
It established independent oversight to oversee major changes, including reforms in procedures, training and supervision, and ordered the launch of a pilot program to test body-wearing cameras in some areas where people are being stopped most frequently.
In August, the city of New York agreed to end the method of storing the names and addresses of people whose cases were rejected after a police search.
The city's appeal is scheduled to be heard orally sometime after March 14, 2014.
The tactics of stopping and searching people have been criticized by a number of civil rights defenders.
In some form, there have been stops and searches for people for about a decade, but recorded searches under the administration of independent mayor Michael Bloomberg rose dramatically to a record 684,330 in 2011, most of them black and Hispanic.
In 2004, four men, all of whom are minorities, filed a class action lawsuit.
Proponents of changes to the stopping and search program carried out by the NY Police Department argue that the changes will end unfair practices, increase the credibility and effectiveness of the police force, and may affect how these practices are used by other police departments.
Opponents argue that the changes will reduce police morale, but not crime, and that this will waste money, but will not solve the broader problem of the police force being under pressure after its numbers have fallen by several thousand over the last decade.
The judge noted that she did not end the practice of stopping and searching people, which is constitutional, but reformed the way the NYPD police department instituted searches.
