George Kerevan: Divided Europe gives Scots a choice
Another day, another ghost story about independence.
This time there is a warning that a condition for an independent Scotland's membership in the EU would be its accession to Schengen.
This gave rise to stories of passport controls at Berwick and barbed wire along Hadrian's Wall.
The truth is that the newspaper Strathclyde mentioned the possible economic benefits of free movement with the rest of Europe, but, as expected, this did not make headlines.
No one has mentioned either that EU Member States spend a lot of time adapting their official laws when it suits them.
Since Scotland is not now in Schengen, the offer of continued inconsistency would be a cheap concession for Brussels in return for whatever it really wants from the Scots.
So it's a pretty weak story.
And it's so old, it's become an excavation, and I heard a journalistic duck saying, "Independence means passport control," at least 40 years ago.
Yet there is an interesting idea in this bearded tale.
Why should an independent Scotland be expected to listen to Europe?
Why trade the London yoke for the Brussels yoke, especially now?
This is the true European story: the great post-war plan to unite Europe has finally failed.
Due to the euro crisis, the so-called Project Europe is officially dead.
Across Europe, parties dedicated to resistance to the EU or the abolition of the euro as a common currency are gaining influence.
Even in Germany, the eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party, founded this year, came out of nowhere and captured nearly five million votes in the September federal election, effectively sweeping the Free Democrats (the equivalent of the British Liberal Democrats) out of the Bundestag.
Domestically, there has always been opposition to the plan to create a federal Europe.
However, the current economic crisis has become a decisive moment.
The austerity dictated by Germany and the European Central Bank, along with the straitjacket strapped to national economies through adherence to the common currency, has led many to believe that the Europe project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments running a high budget deficit - that was true only in Greece.
Rather, it is a euro system that blocks its members from favourable exchange rates for German exporters - and that is what German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of devaluation of the domestic currency, southern Europe has a disadvantage in terms of domestic production compared to Germany.
The only help is to cut revenue and public spending, as Germany encourages.
Behind the current budget and currency problems is a deeper cause of Europe’s sluggish performance.
As a result of the "green" energy policy promoted by Brussels - the code to support French and German companies at the expense of consumers - European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for petrol as it does in the United States.
This is a paralyzing cost disadvantage, as we have already seen in the case of Grangemouth.
Not all of the world’s wage freezes would prevent the European petrochemical industry from being trampled by cheap US shale oil.
The result is a simmering revolt, especially in France, once an enthusiastic supporter of the EU.
After the war, the political elite in France saw the EU as a tool that would keep Germany in check and allow Paris to position itself on the level of Washington in the world.
Berlin, however, no longer needs Paris as a proof of political legitimacy, and has pushed through its own economic policy in Europe, leaving the worn-out French economy to its fate.
The result: Marine Le Pen’s right wing, the anti-European National Front, has just won a major by-election, putting the ruling socialists in third place.
With 24% of the vote, the Front is now the most popular party in France - an early warning to British Labour that they cannot conclude that the splintering of the right will automatically show up on the left.
How does Le Pen deal with her newfound popularity among the white working class?
It would like to use the European elections next year to create an anti-European bloc across the European Parliament against the common currency.
If anti-European parties do well in this election, which is likely, such a bloc may dominate the European Parliament for the first time in history.
It strikes me that in the foreseeable future, the growing anti-European feeling and attitude against the common currency will come together and destroy the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but rather turn into something looser in the sense of a “Europe of (sovereign) nations”, favored by General de Gaulle.
Germany and several of its satellite economies may retain the euro, but France and southern Europe will restore their own currencies.
I expect the United Kingdom to distance itself from this project and join the United States.
But Washington’s increased interest in the Pacific indicates that Britain will be left to the Atlantic cold.
Where is Scotland?
We can choose to be an area of (essentially) Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests - that includes telling Berlin and Brussels when to leave us alone.
I suppose Scotland would do well in a loose arrangement of Europe if it kept its own currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries would be easier in a non-federal Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should take the example of Norway and keep our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is, oddly enough, the most successful non-austerity political movement in Europe, having won by a large majority in 2011 thanks to the opposition to the cuts planned (and implemented) by Labour Chancellor Alistair Darling and the following coalition of Conservatives and Liberal Democrats.
It would be ridiculous if Scotland now voted for independence only to adopt austerity measures dictated by Berlin and Brussels.
Early Puberty: Mature Earlier
Research has shown that African-American and Hispanic women reach puberty earlier than their Caucasian peers.
Physical changes don’t mean puberty is coming.
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are behind this.
Experts say that one of the triggers of earlier puberty may be the obesity epidemic.
The trend of earlier puberty is not so noticeable in boys.
Former CNN reporter Pat Etheridge is a journalist who specializes in children's health and family problems.
Should a mother be horrified when her daughter starts growing breasts and pubic hair at 7 or 8 years old?
At the American Academy of Pediatrics’ annual conference this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these physical changes are quite common among American girls and represent a new standard.
“I’ve spent a lot of time reassuring my parents that this is usually not a sign of rapid development toward full puberty,” Kaplowitz said.
Visible signs of development, such as breast growth, pubic and armpit hair, and body odor, appear earlier in girls.
However, there has been little shift in the age at which first menstruation occurs over the past forty years.
In the United States, the average age is now 12.5 years, compared to 12.75 years in 1970.
“When breasts begin to develop, it takes at least two to three years for the first period to occur,” said Kaplowitz, who is also the author of “Early Puberty in Girls: The Essential Guide to Coping with This Common Problem.”
The most reliable test of how puberty will continue is time.
It is discussed what activates the actual onset of puberty, but if breast growth is accompanied by a growth spurt before the age of 8, the girl is considered "prematurely mature".
In most cases, the process slows down or stops, which can be closely monitored by pediatricians.
Faster growth can be a reason for an endocrinologist to conduct tests to rule out serious problems such as a tumor or cyst.
There are treatments that delay early menstruation and prevent further consequences: premature bone aging, which can eventually lead to stunting of growth and stunting in adulthood.
Recommendations about medications and hormone therapy depend on the child’s age, developmental rate, growth rate, and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
When it comes to drug use, Kaplowitz is cautious, but he acknowledges that “suppressing puberty can alleviate problems with a girl’s behavior and her feelings of being different from her peers.”
Understandably, another big problem: Parents simply don’t want their very young daughters to have periods.
“They’re worried that he might get pregnant or how he’ll handle hygiene,” Kaplowitz said.
“It was a shock,” recalls one woman whose daughter started menstruating at age 10.
Although there were signs and we talked about menstruation, she was not prepared emotionally.
She came home from school scared and angry that she was the first of her friends.
There are many well-known theories about the causes of premature puberty.
However, there is not yet a coherent body of evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, environmental chemicals, or sexual messages in the media are to blame.
Boys, like girls, reach puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz asserts that the most serious reason is the obesity epidemic.
In 2001, he helped conduct a study on girls aged 6 to 9 that linked body fat to the timing of puberty.
Other findings support this conclusion, but there are many other contributing factors.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic women tend to reach puberty earlier than their white counterparts.
The explanations are different.
From a global perspective, early puberty patterns seem to be influenced by everything from economic conditions to climates to genes.
Another puzzle: Although boys develop facial and pubic hair at an early age, the trend toward full-blown early puberty is not as obvious as it is for girls.
Other doctors attending the American Association of Pediatricians (AAP) conference added additional complexity to the topic.
Acne and pubic hair are common even in infants and toddlers.
"We need to be careful about how we identify the actual onset of puberty," said Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Goryeb Children's Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to get instructions from their child’s doctor on how to talk to their child.
"It may mean having to talk to the child sooner than you think," Kaplowitz advised.
If you stay calm, your child will likely respond well.
Girls who develop earlier need reassurance that even if it happens prematurely, this process is a normal part of life.
