New nicotine vaccine may take away the pleasure of smoking
Scientists have developed a nicotine vaccine that can take away the pleasure of smoking a cigarette.
A single dose of the vaccine was able to protect a mouse from nicotine addiction for life.
Before human trials, more tests are needed, which will take several years, but Professor Ronald Crystal of Weill Cornell School of Medicine in New York says the first signs are good.
“We strongly hope that this kind of vaccination strategy can finally help the millions of smokers who have tried to quit and exhausted all the methods available on the market today, but have found that their addiction to nicotine is so strong that it can overcome all current approaches,” Cornell said.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been engineered to carry genetic information to create anti-nicotinic antibodies.
The virus selectively infects liver cells, which then begin to form a steady stream of these antibodies.
Antibodies chase all the nicotine molecules in the bloodstream and neutralize them before they reach the brain, preventing the smoker from getting a nicotine hit.
In tests of vaccinated mice that were additionally supplied with nicotine, they continued their normal activities.
But mice that weren’t vaccinated “calmed down,” the researchers said, which is a sign that nicotine has gotten into their brains.
The experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
Injections had to be given so often to maintain sufficient antibody levels that they proved expensive and impractical.
The cost of new vaccines should be much lower as they convert liver cells into antibody factories.
Professor Crystal said that if future vaccines are completely safe for humans, they could be given to children before they feel like trying a cigarette, thus avoiding nicotine addiction.
Smokers are more likely to quit.
“They will know that if they start smoking again, they will not get any benefit from it because of the nicotine vaccine, and that will help them get rid of this habit,” he said.
British scientists said the results were interesting, but cautioned that more research was needed.
