FAA: Air Passengers Now Allowed to Use Technology Advancements on Planes (But Not Allowed to Call from Their Mobile Phones)
Airline passengers will be able to use their electronic devices "from gate to gate" - in addition to calling from their mobile phones - to read, play games, watch movies and listen to music on the basis of the eagerly awaited new rules issued by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) on Thursday.
Passengers should not expect changes to happen immediately.
How quickly the change will be implemented will vary from airline to airline, FAA Administrator Michael Huerta said at a press conference.
Airlines will have to demonstrate to the FAA how well their aircraft comply with the new rules and that they have updated the cabin crew training manuals and stowage guidelines to comply with the new rules.
The FAA said it had already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic devices in aircraft.
Among the companies that have already passed the plans are Delta and JetBlue.
“Depending on the state of such a plan, we can improve the widespread use of electronic devices very quickly,” the FAA said in a statement.
Currently, passengers are required to turn off their smartphones, tablets and other devices as soon as the aircraft doors close.
They cannot turn them on until the plane reaches a height of 3 kilometers and the captain issues a permit.
Passengers are expected to turn off their devices again when the plane goes down to land, and do not turn them on until the plane is on the ground.
Under the new rules, airlines whose aircraft are properly protected against electronic interference can allow their passengers to use their devices during take-off, landing and taxiing, the FAA said.
Most new transport aircraft and other aircraft that have been modified to allow passengers to use Wifi at higher altitudes are expected to meet these criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the Professional Stewards Association, welcomed the changes.
"Once the new rules are safely in place - and we will work closely with transport companies - it will be a success," Glading said in a statement.
Honestly, we are tired of looking like “guardians.”
However, surfing the Internet, sending e-mails and sms, and downloading data will continue to be prohibited below 3 kilometers above sea level, the agency said.
Passengers will be notified to switch their smartphones, tablets and other devices to air mode.
So still no Words with friends, an online scrabble game played by actor Alec Baldwin on his smartphone in 2011 when he was, as is well known, thrown off an American Airlines plane because he refused to turn off his device when the plane was parked at the gate.
And heavier devices like laptops will have to continue to be stored due to concerns that they might hurt someone if they were flying around the cabin.
Cell phone calls will continue to be banned on board.
The rules for using mobile phones are not set by the FAA, but by the U.S. Federal Committee on Telecommunications.
The FAA may lift the ban on certain electronic devices during take-off and landing.
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the State Transportation Safety Committee, a national transportation security expert at CBS News, said cell phones continue to be considered a risk.
“Mobile phones are really a problem, not only because they can potentially create interference with navigation devices, but we also know from FCC data that they can cause interference to broadcast towers in the air,” Rosenker said.
An industry advisory committee created by the FAA administration to investigate the issue last month proposed that the government allow wider use of electronic devices.
The FAA has been pressured in recent years to ease restrictions on its use.
Critics such as Senator Claire McCaskill, a Democrat from Missouri, argue that there is no valid security reason for this ban.
Restrictions are also becoming increasingly difficult to enforce, as the use of such devices is ubiquitous.
Some studies suggest that up to a third of passengers forget to turn off their devices or ignore them.
The FAA began restricting the use of electronic devices by passengers in 1966 in response to the jamming of navigation and communication equipment when passengers began carrying FM radios with them, a technical achievement of the time.
The new airlines are much more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations' aircraft, but they are also constructed, and approved by the FAA, to be resistant to electronic interference.
For several years, airlines have been offering travelers to use Wi-Fi at travel altitudes.
Plans adapted for Wi-Fi systems are also more resistant to interference.
The vast majority of airlines should adapt to greater use of electronic devices under the new rules, Huert said.
Current electronic devices generally emit far less intense radio transmissions than those of previous generations.
For example, e-readers issue only minimal broadcasts when turning the page.
But broadcasting is stronger when devices download or send data.
Among those pushing to ease restrictions on passengers’ use of these devices is Amazon.com.
In 2011, representatives of the company loaded the airliner with their Kindle e-readers and conducted a test flight, but no problem appeared.
Members of the FAA Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings as to whether these facilities pose any risks.
Douglas Kidd of the National Airline Passenger Association said he believes the interference from these devices is real, even if the risk is minimal.
Other committee members have stated that there are only fragmentary reports from pilots to support the fact that such devices can cause interference to aircraft systems, and most of these reports are very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to order passengers to turn off the device during low-visibility flying.
The travel industry group welcomed the changes and said it was a sensible approach for a travelling public that uses the technology extensively.
"We are delighted that the FAA has recognized that a pleasant travel experience is not at odds with safety," said Roger Dow, executive director of the American Travel Association.
