Scientists shed more light on how tail movements are related to a dog's mood
Previous research has shown that happy dogs wag their tail more to the right (from the dog’s point of view), while nervous dogs wag their tail mostly to the left.
Now, however, scientists say that other dogs can detect and respond to these subtle differences in tail movement.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neurobiologist at the University of Trento, said: “It is well known in humans that the left and right sides of the brain have different links to stimuli that evoke positive or negative emotions.”
We have seen the same thing in other species.
He added that, as with humans, the right side of the brain is responsible for left-handed movements and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres play a different role in emotions.
In an effort to get more information on how dogs respond to the disproportional wag of other dogs' tails, the researchers monitored animals that watched films about other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of these animals and analyzed their behavior.
Apparently, it won't be long before we understand why their tails sometimes go to one side, and sometimes to the other.
Professor Vallortigara said: "We showed dogs films about dogs - either in the natural version or in silhouette - to get rid of any confusing stimuli, and we were also able to adjust the movement of the tail and depict it more to the right or left."
When the animals saw the otherwise bland dog moving its tail to the right (from the point of view of the dog wagging its tail), it remained completely calm.
However, when she noticed the tail turning mostly to the left (again from the point of view of the dog wagging its tail), their heart rate increased and the animals felt insecure.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think dogs would consciously communicate with each other through these movements.
Rather, he believes that dogs have learned from experience which movements they need to watch out for.
He said, “If you meet dogs several times and moving their tail in one direction is repeatedly associated with more friendly behavior, and moving to the right breeds less friendly behavior, you’ll react based on that experience.”
Researchers say the findings can help dog owners, veterinarians, and trainers better understand their animals’ emotions.
Dog behavior expert John Bradshaw, a college veterinary teacher at the University of Bristol, said this was not the first study to examine whether the left and right sides were important to dogs.
Last year, a team from Lincoln University found that dogs turn their heads to the left when they observe an aggressive dog, and to the right when they look at a cheerful dog.
And in another scholarly treatise from Victoria University in Canada, he said: “Dog robots were more likely to be introduced to dogs when they were wagging their tail to the left than to the right, when they were more likely to be insecure than in an Italian study.”
The difference, he said, could be that dogs in these different studies didn’t interpret animals in movies or dog robots quite like dogs.
He explained that a study on how dogs respond to real dogs could help.
"Although there is strong evidence that both sides of the brain are used for different purposes in the case of many different mammals, many details still need to be clarified - and dogs are no exception," he said.
But given how easy it is to record their behavior, it probably won’t be long before we understand why their tail goes to one side and another to the other.
