Google, Samsung and Huawei sued over Nortel patents
The group, which owns thousands of patents from the defunct Nortel, filed a patent infringement lawsuit on Thursday against cell phone makers including Google, a company it re-licensed during an auction in the wake of Nortel's bankruptcy.
The Rockstar consortium, which bought Nortel’s patents for $4.5 billion, sued Samsung Electronics, HTC, Huawei and four other companies in the U.S. District Court for patent infringement.
Rockstar is jointly owned by Apple, Microsoft, Blackberry, Ericsson and Sony.
Google has been accused of infringing on seven patents.
Patents include technology that helps connect search terms on the Internet with relevant advertising, the lawsuit states, which is the core of Google’s search business.
Representatives of Samsung, Huawei, HTC and Rockstar were not immediately available.
Samsung, Huawei and HTC are making phones that run on Google’s Android operating system, which competes strongly with Apple and Microsoft’s mobile products.
In 2011, Google made a $900 million initial bid for Nortel's patents.
Google increased its offer several times and eventually offered up to $4.4 billion.
After Nortel was defeated by Rockstar in the patent battle, Google acquired Motorola Mobility for $12.5 billion, a deal motivated in part by a group of Motorola patents.
"Despite the failure to bid for the patents at the auction, Google has infringed and continues to infringe on the patents," the lawsuit said.
Rockstar is seeking increased damages from Google because, according to it, the patent infringement by Google is being committed intentionally, as the lawsuit alleges.
