Egypt Appoints First Freely Elected President
Mohamed Morsi has taken the inaugural oath, but his triumphant day will hardly end the political unrest in Egypt.
ISLAMIST Mohamed Morsi promised a “new Egypt” when he was inaugurated as the country’s first freely elected president, after Hosni Mubarak, who had been deposed 16 months earlier.
In his inauguration before the High Constitutional Court, Morsi also became the first freely elected Islamic president in the Arab world and the fifth Egyptian head of state since the overthrow of the monarchy approximately 60 years ago.
He was sworn in before 18 judges dressed in black robes in a mansion built overlooking the Nile that resembles an ancient Egyptian temple.
“We are striving for a better tomorrow, a new Egypt and a second republic,” Morsi said at a ceremony broadcast live on state television.
“Today, the Egyptian people laid the foundation for a new life of absolute freedom, true democracy and stability,” said Morsi, a 60-year-old US-trained engineer and member of the Muslim Brotherhood, a fundamentalist group that has been under intense attack by governments for most of 84 years since its inception as an illegal organization.
When Morsi arrived shortly after 11 a.m. in a small motorcade, hundreds of soldiers and police were guarding the building.
Only a few hundred supporters gathered outside the courthouse to celebrate the president, and unlike the presidential pomp of the Mubarak period, traffic was only briefly stopped so that the motorcade could pass through the usually busy road connecting the city center with the suburbs to the south.
Morsi’s personal prestige, derided as the Muslim Brotherhood’s non-charismatic “reserve tire,” has grown sharply since his victory and his speech on Friday, which aimed to present him not only as an Islamist candidate but also to all those who want to lead the rebellion against the authoritarian Mubarak to the end.
“Egypt today is a civil, national, constitutional and modern state,” Morsi said, dressed in a blue social suit with a red tie to the judges in the wood-paneled chamber where he was sworn in.
Morsi later traveled to Cairo University to give his inaugural address.
While standing at attention, he received an official welcome from the military band that played the national anthem.
Military commander Field Marshal Hussein Tantawi was present.
His arrival was accompanied by chants of “army and people are one hand” from the mouths of hundreds of people gathered in the university’s main lecture hall.
The University of Cairo was founded in 1908 as a center for secular education and later in the 1970s became a bastion of Islamic student movements.
Morsi took a symbolic oath on Friday in Tahrir Square, the birthplace of the revolution that ended Mubarak’s authoritarian rule last year, and vowed to retake the presidential powers taken from his office by the military council that took them from the ousted leader.
But by agreeing to take an official oath in court rather than before parliament, as is customary, he has submitted to the will of the military, indicating that the power struggle will continue.
Morsi’s speech in Tahrir Square was full of dramatic populist gestures.
There will probably be police specialists in the ghettos, they are supposed to ease the tension
In the future, police specialists should work in ghettos in the Czech Republic.
They'd spend up to half their errands here.
They would supervise the order and solve problems.
Thanks to their knowledge of the environment, they should contribute to reducing tensions between people from poor places and residents from the surrounding area.
In its proposal to reduce security risks, the Ministry of the Interior counts on this.
He said it would help to improve the situation in the country by “prompting the provision of social housing”.
The document was discussed by the government.
According to the analysis, there were about 300 poor houses and neighborhoods in the Czech Republic a few years ago.
Some 80,000 people lived there, mainly Romani people.
The adults in the ghettos were out of work, families were dependent on benefits, children ended up in "special" schools.
Usury was rampant.
According to experts, the problem areas have since grown by a hundred.
Relationships between their residents and others are intensifying.
Anti-Romani marches were held in several places.
People from the surrounding area also joined the extremists.
According to the Interior Ministry, it is difficult for police in ghetto areas to maintain security and order.
The fundamental condition is "the consistent application of an equal approach in law enforcement".
But this cannot be achieved without detailed knowledge of the place and the people.
A specialist would run errands in the ghetto, where he would spend up to half his service, the rest would serve in his district.
In a troubled location, he would oversee order.
He would also know the locals, so he could better solve problems or misdemeanors.
"Thanks to the established trust, specialists will more easily be able to prevent a number of unlawful acts," the Interior Ministry said in a statement.
Specialists in the ghettos would receive allowances of between 500 and 1000 crowns per month.
The introduction of special police officers into problem areas is to be covered by Norwegian funds.
The budget is about 600,000 euros (about 15.5 million crowns).
The Czech Republic pays 15 percent of the amount, the funds 85 percent.
Preparations began this year, and a detailed proposal is now being prepared.
The project is scheduled to last until 2016.
The authors were inspired by their neighbors.
This mechanism has been successfully applied in Slovakia for several years, where the problem with socially excluded localities is incomparably higher than in the Czech Republic.
"There are so-called Romani settlements here," the authors of the report said.
How many specialists there should be in the Czech Republic is not yet clear.
The answer is to give an analysis that will identify places where a special policeman would be needed.
It will also depend on how much money the police will be able to release each year after the project ends.
According to the project proposal, the selected police officers will first undergo an internship in Slovakia.
There should be 50 members per year in this training.
They will be the most suitable candidates.
There should also be special education for police officers working in the ghettos.
According to the authors, social housing would help to improve the situation.
It should motivate and lead to integration.
According to the interior design, there would be three categories.
A minimum standard would be met by hostels with well-defined rules, such as the number of people per room.
The middle standard would be in smaller apartments.
Higher standards would have social housing comparable to regular housing.
Tenants would have to implement an integration plan that social workers would put together with them.
They would have to follow the accommodation rules, take care of their health, send their children to school, retrain and actively look for work.
If they were to be included, they would move up to a higher standard of living.
According to the Interior Ministry, the transitional housing system should last at least 30 years until the next generation grows up “in a pro-integrationally motivated environment”.
The social housing model is being prepared by local development and labour ministries.
It is to be proposed by the end of the year.
Karel Drábek: Uhlířský vrch - one of our youngest volcanoes.
Uhlířský vrch is a prominent hill 3 km southeast of Bruntál.
Along with several others, it is evidence of volcanic activity in Low Jeseník at a time (from a geological point of view) recent.
The last eruptions were at the beginning of the Quaternary.
Viewed from a greater distance, on top of Uhlířský vrch there is a conspicuous white plastered Baroque pilgrimage church of Our Lady of Help, built in the years 1755 - 1765.
It replaced the original wooden pilgrimage chapel.
The inn next to the church did not survive.
Shortly after the church was completed, an alley of four rows of linden trees, about 1 km long, was planted.
The Way of the Cross on Uhlířské vrch is already the third version, the original one stood here after 1916, the second one, from 2001, lasted only until 2004.
On the fifteen stops there are wooden sculptures made by local artist František Nedomlel.
He used different types of trees from the Low Jeseníky region.
Similarly, the pedestals from the rocks from the area form an interesting geological exposition.
The name of the sponsor is also shown at each stop.
The coal hill is the remnant of a young volcano.
Although data from radiometric age measurements vary somewhat, the last eruption here was about 1.5 million years ago.
It is therefore younger than the Great Roudny (3.3 million years old) and older than the Venus Volcano (0.8 million years old).
The volcano was born with an explosion.
In doing so, she ejected significant amounts of volcanic ash along with rock fragments from the bedrock, which gained a reddish-brown color by burning.
At the end of this phase, lava flowed to the surface - today it is a layer of porous basalt up to 13 meters thick.
The second eruption ejected red, brownish-red, and in some places black tuffs.
Their layer is powerful up to 50 meters and its part is accessible in the wall of the quarry.
The tuffs contain volcanic eruptions of up to 1 metre in size, and the second eruption ended with a lava flow.
At the end of the activity, lava flowed out of the volcano, which today forms up to 50 m thick layer of slag basalt.
Volcanoes that alternate the ejection of volcanic ash with lava discharges are the most common type of volcano.
Because they are actually composed of layers, they are called stratovolcanoes.
The original volcanic cone was gradually subject to erosion.
However, it was threatened by mining rocks in the quarry on the south side.
The most intensive mining took place here between 1953 and 1962.
Tuffs were added to the concrete, which was then lighter and had better thermal insulation properties.
Under the pressure of experts and the public, the mining was able to stop and thus preserve this unique place.
However, the problem lies in the porosity and small cohesiveness of the rocks, which quickly weather, crumble and slide down the slope.
The quarry is disappearing quite quickly.
To make the situation even more complicated, the warm, south-facing slope is an ideal place for some rare plant and animal species.
The repair is therefore problematic, but over time it will be necessary to select and maintain the characteristic geological profile.
It is nothing new, similar profiles are maintained in a number of important locations.
You can get to Uhlířský vrch by following the green tourist trail from Bruntál or from Slezský Kočov.
Motorists can use the free parking at the beginning of the linden alley, where the short nature trail begins.
