Six companies out of ten are preparing for the new Civil Code.
Six out of ten companies are in intensive preparation for the forthcoming effectiveness of the new Civil Code and the Business Corporations Act from 1 January 2014.
Only 8 percent of respondents said they had not addressed issues related to the two key codes in their company at all.
This is the result of a survey conducted by the law firm Ambruz & Dark Deloitte Legal, which polled 108 Czech companies.
As the two key codes come into effect, many managers are only now beginning to realize at the last minute how they can have a significant impact on their company’s business.
In our opinion, the biggest changes in private law in the last 50 years will affect all citizens and companies in the Czech Republic.
Because of political lashings, the business sector has long been uncertain about whether or not revolutionary changes will eventually take place.
"However, they now have only a few weeks left to make the transition to the new law without complications for their companies," said Jan Spáčil, partner of Ambruz & Dark Deloitte Legal.
Of the 61 percent of companies heavily engaged in the new laws, 26 percent said their companies had already taken all the necessary measures to be ready in time.
Furthermore, 35 percent of the companies are preparing to take the necessary measures in the near future.
In contrast, one in five companies has not yet dealt with recodification, but still has a concrete idea of how to prepare for it.
A total of 11 percent have no opinion and are unable to assess the issue.
Only 8% of companies admit that they have not yet addressed issues related to recodification.
The most important legal issue related to the new Civil Code for the largest number of surveyed companies is the conclusion of new contracts (21%), followed by the resolution of business conditions (16%), as well as changes in the land register and liability for damages (ten percent each).
In the case of contracts, one of the most significant innovations of the whole recodification will take place, namely the unification of the contract regulation only within the framework of the new Civil Code.
The current parallel regulation in the Civil and Commercial Codes will cease to exist, as a result of which contract law should become clearer for citizens and entrepreneurs.
"In the case of entrepreneurs, the new regulation will offer many novelties with an emphasis on greater freedom of relationship arrangement," said Lukáš Poddán, attorney at law at Ambruz & Dark Deloitte Legal.
In connection with the Business Corporations Act, almost a quarter of companies consider the most important topic to be the issue of increasing the responsibility of statutory bodies.
The following are topics related to changes in the convening and running of the general meeting (15 percent) and representation of the company (14 percent).
The new legislation means tightening obligations and possible impacts for statutory bodies, especially in a situation where a company is threatened with bankruptcy or gets into bankruptcy.
"In practice, this means that if members of boards of directors and company executives do not act with the care of a proper manager and do not avert the impending bankruptcy of the company, they may lose the benefits gained for the performance of the office in the last two years," Spáčil added.
