Travels through mud, river and jungle and provides free medical care
Dr. Georges Bwelle provides free medical care in villages in Cameroon.
Bwelle and his team treat hundreds of patients almost every weekend
There are not many doctors in the countries of West Africa; only one per 5,000 inhabitants.
Vote here or via your mobile phone.
Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of the top 10 nominees for the 2013 CNN Heroes of the Year Award.
You can vote for him or any of the top 10 nominees in the 2013 CNN Heroes of the Year competition.
The winner will receive $250,000 to continue their extraordinary work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle has watched his father fall unconscious over and over again and has gone to hospitals that were not equipped to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident near Cameroon's capital Yaounde in 1981.
At first, he was treated only with a broken arm, but then he developed an infection that spread to his brain, where he developed a hematoma that caused problems throughout his life.
“There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,” says Georges Bwelle.
We'd have to take him outside of Cameroon if we had the money.
Instead, Bwelle spent years transporting his father to overcrowded clinics and hospitals, where he received the kind of treatment that was simply available.
“It’s not easy,” says Bwelle.
You can leave the house at five in the morning, rush to the hospital to be there first, but you're not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some people die just because they have to wait.
The situation has not changed much since Bwelle’s father died in 2002.
According to the World Health Organization, there is only one doctor per 5,000 inhabitants in Cameroon.
For comparison, the ratio in the United States is one doctor per 413 inhabitants.
And even if the Cameroonians could visit the doctor, many would not be able to afford it.
Two out of five people in this country live below the poverty line, and nearly three-quarters of health care spending in this country is private.
“The only problem they have is poverty,” says Bwelle.
They cannot enjoy life because of poverty.
When Bwelle saw his father and many of his compatriots suffering, he decided to do something about it.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers performed 700 free surgeries last year.
He became a vascular surgeon himself at Yaounde Central Hospital.
And he founded the non-profit organization ASCOVIME, whose members visit rural areas on weekends to provide free medical care.
Since 2008, almost 32,000 people have helped with their group of volunteers.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 people cram themselves into vans, attach themselves to the roofs of medical supplies, and travel through rough terrain to villages in need of help.
It is not always accompanied by happiness.
More than once, vehicles have to push through the river and mud.
But when they arrive, they are greeted as true heroes: feasting, singing, and dancing, and the best accommodations the community can offer.
In these villages, free medical care is a real reason to celebrate, and Bwelle - with her broad smile and unbridled energy - is very willing to get involved in the local merriment.
The next day, the team begins to treat hundreds of patients.
“We have 500 patients on each expedition,” says Bwelle.
They come to the village from a radius of 60 kilometers, on foot.
During each of these weekends, doctors provide various medical assistance.
Many are treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasitic diseases, and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others can get crutches or gifted glasses or a birth certificate for free - a document that the school requires, but which many poor families simply cannot afford.
In the evening, the team performs simple operations under local anaesthesia.
Operations are usually performed in a school building, city hall, or home; after surgery, the patient gets up and goes to a recovery site to make room for another patient.
Using light from the generator, the operating room, and hygiene equipment, Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early hours of the morning.
It’s exhausting, but village musicians usually help the team not to lose motivation.
“To stay awake and keep working, they play drums all night,” says Bwelle.
On Sunday, the team heads back to town, tired but proud of their work.
This group, consisting of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students, performed 700 operations for free last year and realizes that their help can mean a lot to the local population.
One man said he'd be able to work again after hernia surgery.
“It will change our family’s future,” the man said.
In addition to organizing these weekend clinics and working as a surgeon at Bwelle Hospital, he also works at night for private medical clinics around the city of Yaounde.
He says that this second work funds about 60% of his non-profit activities; the rest is covered by private contributions.
“I’m not sure when she’s actually sleeping,” says Katie O’Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia and a volunteer for Bwelle’s group.
He is always either in the hospital or trying to raise money for the organization to do these campaigns.
For medical and nursing students like O'Malley who have come from the United States or Europe to join Bwelle on his mission, it's a great practice they wouldn't get at home.
“We washed Dr. Bwelle’s hands thoroughly, removing blood stains or holding his tools,” O’Malley said.
As a second-year medical student in America, you'll never experience that.
Students volunteers usually pay their own way to Cameroon and often arrive with donated medical supplies.
But once they arrive in Yaounde, Bwelle provides them with food, transportation, and study.
“He’s definitely a hero,” says O’Malley.
He gives his life to this organization, and his desire to help the people of Cameroon is endless.
It's not a burden to Bwelle.
Helping others to live happier lives, fulfilling the promise he made to his father, is something that brings him great joy.
“I’m so happy when I do this job,” says Bwelle.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
Make people laugh, ease their pain - that's why I do it.
